```python
def longest_common_subsequence(X, Y):
    m, n = len(X), len(Y)
    # Create a 2D DP table - lcs[i][j] stores length of LCS of X[0..i-1] and Y[0..j-1]
    lcs = [[0] * (n+1) for _ in range(m+1)]

    for i in range(1, m+1):
        for j in range(1, n+1):
            if X[i-1] == Y[j-1]:  # If current characters match, add 1 to the diagonal value
                lcs[i][j] = lcs[i-1][j-1] + 1
            else:
                lcs[i][j] = max(lcs[i-1][j],  lcs[i][j-1])  # Take the maximum of deletion

    # Reconstruct the LCS string from the table
    i, j = m, n
    lcs_string = []
    while i > 0 and j > 0:
        if X[i-1] == Y[j-1]:
            lcs_string.insert(0, X[i-1])  # Prepend (track backward LCS path)
            i -= 1
            j -= 1
        else:
            if lcs[i-1][j] > lcs[i][j-1]:
                i -= 1
            else:
                j -= 1
    return ''.join(lcs_string)

# Example usage:
longest_common_subsequence("AGGTAB", "GXTXAYB")  # Outputs "GTAB"
```

The reconstructed part builds the LCS string by backtracking through the table, which efficiently gives us the longest common subsequence of the input strings. The space optimization over a naive dynamic programming approach achieves linear space complexity by leveraging the 1-D sequence ancestry property (each substring has a unique path at most).
